‹g¬]<?php exit; ?>a:1:{s:7:"content";O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1262";s:4:"name";s:11:"Sore Throat";s:4:"slug";s:11:"sore-throat";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1262";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:4058:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">A sore throat or pharyngitis is pain, irritation or scratchiness of the throat that usually worsens with swallowing. Although everyone, at one time or the other, has suffered from a sore throat, it is most common among children than adolescents and adults. Approximately 10% of children who visit the doctor each year have a sore throat.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">40% of cases of children taken to the doctor with a sore throat often get diagnosed as viral.</span>

<b>Symptoms Of Sore Throat</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Symptoms of sore throat depend on the cause. However, below are a few of the common symptoms:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pain or scratchy feeling in the throat</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pain that becomes worse with talking or swallowing.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Trouble with swallowing.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Muffled voice.</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Sore throat caused by infection might result in the following symptoms:</b>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Cough</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fever</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sneezing</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Headache</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Body ache</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Causes Of Sore Throat</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The virus responsible for flu and common cold can also cause sore throats. Rarely do bacterial infections lead to sore throats. Viral infections that might lead to sore their include:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Flu</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Common colds</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Chickenpox</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Measles</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Risk Factors Of Sore Throat</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Even though anyone can have a sore throat, certain factors can trigger its occurrence, including:</span>

<b>Age: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Children and teens have a higher risk of developing sore throats.</span>

<b>Smoking tobacco: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Smoking and even passive smoking can irritate the throat.</span>

<b>Allergies: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Reaction to molds, dust or pet dander increases the chance of sore throat.</span>

<b>Exposure to toxic irritants: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Particles from household chemicals and fossil fuels can irritate the throat.</span>

<b>Prevention of sore throat</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One of the best ways to prevent sore throat is to practice good hygiene and avoiding germs that cause sore throats. Here are some personal hygiene habits you can start practicing today:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Always wash your hands frequently and thoroughly before eating or after using the toilet.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Don't share food, utensils or drinking glasses.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Avoid physical contact with sick people</span></li>
</ul>
